        {
          "name": "USACE Beneficial Use of Dredged Material (BUDM) Implementation",
          "location": "Mobile Bay, Alabama (2014-present)",
          "description": "USACE aims to beneficially use at least 70% of dredged material for marsh creation, shoreline stabilization, and habitat restoration. This material is used for multiple projects, including the Dauphin Island Causeway and the Deer River Coastal Marsh Stabilization, providing cost savings and restoring vital protective habitats."
        },
        {
          "name": "USACE Mobile Harbor Modernization & Beneficial Use on Dauphin Island Causeway",
          "location": "Mobile Bay, Alabama (2014-2025)",
          "description": "USACE deepened the harbor to 50 feet (Economic Resilience). Dredged material from harbor deepening is used to build new marsh habitat behind breakwaters along the Causeway. Dredging helps rebuild barrier islands by providing the necessary material (sediment). This directly stabilizes critical infrastructure (the evacuation road) and creates habitat buffers, reducing storm surge impacts on the mainland. Channel deepening allows for larger vessel calls (measured economic gain). BU creates ~80 acres of marsh (measured ecological output), directly protecting the island's only access/evacuation road from storm impacts.",
          "references": [
            "https://www.alports.com/alabama-port-authority-celebrates-completion-of-mobile-harbor-modernization-project-with-ribbon-cutting-ceremony/",
            "https://www.sam.usace.army.mil/Media/News-Stories/Article/3886253/mobile-districts-thin-layer-placement-provides-sustainable-management-in-mobile/"
          ]
        },
        {
          "name": "Port of Houston Dredged Material Mitigation (Project 11) - Barrier Island/Ecosystem Restoration",
          "location": "Port of Houston, Texas (Ongoing)",
          "description": "Local example of doing this 'at scale' that can help jump-start similar projects in Mobile Bay. Project 11 requires mandatory use of dredged material from channel deepening to create hundreds of acres of marsh, bird islands, and oyster reefs. This addresses Mobile's critical gap for managing its massive dredge volume, shifting disposal from 'waste' to barrier island building material to mitigate ecological damage. This demonstrates a proven approach for large-scale barrier island and ecosystem restoration using dredged material. Output Measured: Project 11 is creating 260 acres of oyster mitigation and building up to 800 acres of new marsh habitat.",
          "references": [
            "https://www.expandthehoustonshipchannel.com/project-overview/",
            "https://www.waterwaysjournal.net/2020/04/08/mobile-harbor-capital-dredging-marine-industry-federal-funding/"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "barrier_island_restoration",
      "name": "Barrier Island Restoration",
      "description": "Comprehensive restoration of barrier islands to maintain their protective function, prevent breaches, and preserve critical habitats. Barrier islands serve as the first line of defense against storms for mainland communities. Rebuilding barrier islands creates the best resilience for ports and coastal infrastructure at the lowest cost point in the regional system, because it addresses the root cause: loss of the barrier/wave attenuation. This strategy provides regional first-line defense (wave attenuation and surge reduction across all assets) rather than site-specific, last-line defense protection. A healthy barrier island system reduces the frequency of permanent inundation and pushes back against sea level rise, delaying or reducing the urgency of having to raise bulkheads and quay walls at terminals (hardened gray infrastructure), which would be extremely expensive.",
