        "cost_savings": "Investing in nature-based solutions like barrier island restoration is viewed as an effective use of capital to reduce the eventual, much larger cost of hard infrastructure adaptation. Projected adaptation investment of between $1.18 billion and $4.07 billion by 2050 for the Port of Mobile region could be significantly reduced or delayed."
      },
      "business_value_impacts": {
        "operational_expenses": {
          "description": "Globally, 32% of the total estimated value at risk to ports is due to hurricanes and typhoons, and this risk is heavily concentrated in the U.S. Gulf Coast region. The shipping and shipbuilding industry's #1 risk from coastal hazards is Physical Damage to Shipyard Infrastructure.",
          "risk_reduction": "Modeled data from similar USACE restoration projects shows flood risk reduction up to 87% for critical infrastructure during a benchmark storm (Source: USACE Willapa Bay Project). Surge reduction is small, but wave attenuation is highly effective."
        },
        "capital_expenses": {
          "description": "Barrier islands slow the timeline for needing to build ports higher to adapt to rising sea levels, which will be up to 40 centimeters (15.7 inches) between 2020 and 2050. A healthy barrier island system reduces the frequency of permanent inundation and pushes back against sea level rise, delaying or reducing the urgency of having to raise bulkheads and quay walls at terminals.",
          "cost_avoidance": "Hardened Gray Infrastructure (raising bulkheads and quay walls) would be extremely expensive. Barrier island restoration provides cost-effective alternative that delays or reduces need for these capital-intensive adaptations."
